A marriage is voidable under Section 12 of the Hindu Marriage Act, 1955 (HMA) on several grounds, including: 

1. if the marriage is not consummated due to the incapacity of the respondent (Section 12(1)(a) HMA); 
2. if the respondent has consented to the marriage under duress or undue influence (Section 12(1)(c) HMA); 
3. if the respondent was suffering from mental disorder, making them unfit for marriage (Section 12(1)(b) HMA); 
4. if the respondent has been suffering from a virulent and incurable form of leprosy (Section 12(1)(d) HMA); 
5. if the respondent has been suffering from a venereal disease in a communicable form (Section 12(1)(e) HMA); 
6. if the respondent has renounced the world by entering any religious order (Section 12(1)(f) HMA); 
7. if the respondent has not attained the age of marriage as per the provisions of Section 5(iii) of the HMA (Section 12(1)(g) HMA, as per the amendment in the Prohibition of Child Marriage Act, 2006, read with the HMA).

